T1  - Determination of Warranty Reserves
AU  - Menke, Warren W.
Y1  - 1969/06/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.15.10.B542
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.15.10.B542
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-542
EP  - B-549
VL  - 15
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Cost of warranty claims for failure of a product is an identifiable business cost. Methods of calculation are presented for determining this cost item for a linear prorata rebate plan and for a lump sum rebate plan where the customer receives a fixed amount for any failures within the warranty period. It is shown that a calculable amount, usually modest for good products, can be allocated by the manufacturer to a warranty reserve fund to cover the expected risks of warranty claims. Additionally, it is shown that the insight gained by a manufacturer about the components contributing to warranty reserve funding can furnish him with new marketing strategies.
AB  - Cost of warranty claims for failure of a product is an identifiable business cost. Methods of calculation are presented for determining this cost item for a linear prorata rebate plan and for a lump sum rebate plan where the customer receives a fixed amount for any failures within the warranty period. It is shown that a calculable amount, usually modest for good products, can be allocated by the manufacturer to a warranty reserve fund to cover the expected risks of warranty claims. Additionally, it is shown that the insight gained by a manufacturer about the components contributing to warranty reserve funding can furnish him with new marketing strategies.
